Here are two complete implementations of binary search in JavaScript:

// 1️⃣ Iterative version
function binarySearchIterative(arr, target) {
  let left = 0;
  let right = arr.length - 1;

  while (left <= right) {
    const mid = Math.floor((left + right) / 2);
    if (arr[mid] === target) {
      return mid; // Target found
    }
    if (arr[mid] < target) {
      left = mid + 1; // Search right half
    } else {
      right = mid - 1; // Search left half
    }
  }
  return -1; // Target not found
}

// 2️⃣ Recursive version
function binarySearchRecursive(arr, target, left = 0, right = arr.length - 1) {
  if (left > right) {
    return -1; // Base case: target not found
  }

  const mid = Math.floor((left + right) / 2);
  if (arr[mid] === target) {
    return mid; // Target found
  }
  if (arr[mid] < target) {
    // Search in the right half
    return binarySearchRecursive(arr, target, mid + 1, right);
  } else {
    // Search in the left half
    return binarySearchRecursive(arr, target, left, mid - 1);
  }
}

// --- How they work ---
// 1️⃣ Iterative:
//    • We keep two pointers, left and right, that bound the current search window.
//    • In each loop iteration we calculate mid.
//    • If arr[mid] equals target, we return mid.
//    • If arr[mid] < target, we discard the left half by setting left = mid + 1.
//    • If arr[mid] > target, we discard the right half by setting right = mid - 1.
//    • The loop ends when left surpasses right, meaning the target is not in the array.

// 2️⃣ Recursive:
//    • The function receives the same left and right bounds as parameters.
//    • Base case: if left > right, the target is not present.
//    • We compute mid and compare arr[mid] with target.
//    • Depending on the comparison, we recursively call the function on either the
//      right half (mid + 1 to right) or the left half (left to mid - 1).
//    • The recursion unwinds, returning the index when found or -1 when the base
//      case is hit.

// --- Test examples ---
const sortedArray = [3, 7, 11, 15, 23, 42, 56];
console.log(binarySearchIterative(sortedArray, 15)); // → 3
console.log(binarySearchIterative(sortedArray, 8));  // → -1
console.log(binarySearchRecursive(sortedArray, 23)); // → 4
console.log(binarySearchRecursive(sortedArray, 1));  // → -1

Binary search is an efficient algorithm for finding a target value in a sorted array. It operates by initializing two pointers, low and high, at the start and end of the array, respectively. In each iteration, it calculates the middle index mid = (low + high) // 2 and compares the value at that index with the target. If they match, the index is returned. If the target is less than the middle value, the high pointer is moved to mid - 1; if greater, the low pointer is moved to mid + 1. This process repeats until the pointers cross, indicating the target is not present.

Preconditions: The array must be sorted in ascending order; otherwise, the algorithm may return incorrect results. The elements should be comparable using the <, >, == operators.

Time Complexity: Each iteration halves the remaining search space, resulting in O(log n) comparisons for an array of size n. In the worst case, if the target is not present, the algorithm will perform about log₂n comparisons.

Python Implementation:

def binary_search(arr, target):
    low, high = 0, len(arr) - 1
    while low <= high:
        mid = (low + high) // 2
        if arr[mid] == target:
            return mid
        elif arr[mid] < target:
            low = mid + 1
        else:
            high = mid - 1
    return -1  # target not found

The function returns the index of the target if found, otherwise -1. This implementation follows the standard binary search pattern and satisfies the preconditions and time complexity discussed above.

def fibonacci(n):
    """Return the nth Fibonacci number using recursion."""
    # Base cases
    if n == 0:
        return 0
    if n == 1:
        return 1
    # Recursive step
    return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2)

# Example usage:
# print(fibonacci(10))  # Output: 55

